Date: Fri 17 Nov 2017
Source: Gente Digital, Espa√±a [in Spanish, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
http://www.gentedigital.es/fuenlabrada/noticia/2270438/la-uci-del-hospital-de-fuenlabrada-sigue-cerrada-tras-el-brote-de-aspergillus/


Sources at the Fuenlabrada hospital confirmed that they may be able to re-open the ICU by the middle of next week. "They are taking cultures and are on a deadline," they said.

Those affected by the fungus [_Aspergillus_] remain in stable condition and were transferred to a recovery room where they are able to treat the disease. There were 2 people, a 60 year old and an 80 year old, who were in the ICU for a general infection in one of the cases, and the other case was post-operative, explained Joaquin Alvarez, the head of the ICU.

The health facility will complete an "absolute cleaning" as well as a series of "exhaustive biologic controls" explained the medical director, Antonio Zapatero. In addition, they will take apart all equipment in the unit and collect specimens to determine the origin of the infection. This process includes the "cleaning of all respirators" and all materials and medical equipment.

After learning about the cases, the hospital administration informed patients and their families and friends, as well as the different services [departments] in the health facility and the works council [unions?]. In addition, in coordination with the Madrid Health department, they notified SUMMA 112 [Emergency Medical Services of Madrid] and the nearby hospitals, where patients needing ICU care will be referred until there is no longer a risk of infection in the ICU.

The detection of these 2 cases, combined with identifying 2 additional suspected cases, led to the decision to transfer these patients and an additional 4 patients requiring continuous care in an ICU to the recovery room. "These are patients who are clinically compromised and with immunocompromising conditions," explained Alvarez.

Nevertheless, the management team of the health facility ruled out any risk for the population. "The situation is normal," said Zapatero, who said that these infections are usual in hospitals.

On her part, the chief of prevention [infection control] of the hospital, Laura Moratilla, said that collection of "routine specimens" from the ICU and operating rooms, as well isolation rooms and other areas, reduces risks.

