[Aspergillosis is an infection caused by the fungus _Aspergillus_ species, most commonly _Aspergillus fumigatus_ and _A. flavus_. Invasive aspergillosis usually occurs in people who have severe/prolonged granulocytopenia or are immunosuppressed for other reasons. Aspergilli can also cause allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis in people with underlying lung diseases.

_Aspergillus_ is found everywhere in the environment, such as soil, decomposing plant matter, household dust, building materials, plants, food, and water. Transmission usually occurs through inhalation of airborne spores. Hospital-acquired infections can be sporadic, or clusters of cases can occur due to inhalation of spores, such as following building construction.

_Aspergillus_ is an angio-invasive fungus, and definitive diagnosis requires histopathological evidence of infection or a positive culture from a normally sterile site. _Aspergillus_ appears microscopically as septated hyphae with acute angle branching. Other diagnostic methods include detection of galactomannan and beta-D-glucan (both cell wall components of _Aspergillus_ as well as other fungi) and polymerase chain reaction (PCR).

The news report above does not give any clinical or epidemiological details concerning the aspergillosis that occurred in the 2 hospitalized patients. More information on this outbreak would be appreciated from knowledgeable sources.

Fuenlabrada, with a population of 197 836 residents in 2009, is a city and municipality in the Madrid Metropolitan Area, Spain, located 22.5 km (14 miles) southwest of the capital (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuenlabrada). - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5453247,43118.]
